# Changelog Update Rule

When adding **user-facing features, improvements, or fixes**, update the changelog.

## When to Update Changelog

✅ **Update for:**
- New features users can see/use
- UI/UX improvements
- Bug fixes that affect user experience
- Security improvements
- Performance improvements users will notice

❌ **Skip for:**
- Internal refactoring (no user impact)
- Code cleanup
- Test additions
- Documentation updates
- Build configuration changes

## How to Update

Edit `/lib/constants/changelog.ts`:

```typescript
export const changelog: ChangelogVersion[] = [
  {
    version: '1.5.0',  // Increment appropriately
    date: 'January 25, 2026',  // Today's date
    entries: [
      {
        version: '1.5.0',
        date: 'January 25, 2026',
        category: 'feature',  // or 'improvement', 'fix', 'security'
        title: 'Short, Clear Feature Name',
        description: 'User-friendly description of what this does and why it matters to users.',
      },
    ],
  },
  // ... existing versions
];
```

## Categories

| Category | Use For |
|----------|---------|
| `feature` | New capabilities/features |
| `improvement` | Enhancements to existing features |
| `fix` | Bug fixes |
| `security` | Security updates |

## Writing Good Entries

✅ **Good:**
- Title: "Bug Reporter"
- Description: "Report issues directly from the app. We'll automatically capture context to help fix problems faster."

❌ **Bad:**
- Title: "Error Logging System"
- Description: "Added ErrorLogger service with API endpoints for error capture and AI analysis."

**Key:** Write for end users, not developers. Focus on benefits, not implementation.

## Version Numbering

- **1.X.0**: New features
- **1.x.Y**: Improvements or fixes
- Group related changes under the same version

## Example Commit Pattern

When committing feature changes:
```bash
git commit -m "feat: add feature name
- Implement feature
- Update changelog with user-facing description"
```

